<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
<a name="kurai-da"In</a> this usage, <strong>@HI{{kurai}}</strong> indicates an example (which did not actually happen)
the extent of which is being emphasised.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{ikura@KJ{{relax}}i@KJ{{place}}demo@KT{{shawa-}}<strong>kurai</strong>@KJ{{adhere}}iteirudeshou.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      Even though it is a cheap place, there should at least be a shower.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>

<p>
<a name="kurai-wa-nai">With</a> a negative predicate, <strong>@HI{{kurai}}</strong> expresses a superlative.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{@KJ{{mountain^rice*field}}san'<strong>kurai</strong>yoku@KJ{{thing}}wo@KJ{{forget}}reru@KJ{{person}}
      <strong>hainai</strong>.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      There's no-one as forgetful as Mr. Yamada.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
<p>

<p>
<a name="kurainara"><strong>@HI{{kurainara}}</strong></a> expresses the idea that one would be better off
doing something else rather than whatever is expressed by the preceding clause.

<table class="sentence">
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
      @HI{{son'nakotowosuru<strong>kurainara</strong>@KJ{{death}}nda@KJ{{direction}}gamashita.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
      I would rather die tha do such a thing.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</p>
